. 2015
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="94361F62FF9F5B49F9B1BB00BB3D332C" blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<taxonomicName id="538964E1FF9F5B49F9B1BB00B8CA3060" box="[199,413,1364,1388]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis id="A6FDC370FF9F5B49F9B1BB00B8CA3060" box="[199,413,1364,1388]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Bucardium ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49F8DABB00B8BB3060" box="[428,492,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) has an almost orbicular shell shape, slightly higher than large, sub-equilateral, with a long, barely convex, gently sloping antero-dorsal margin, and a very short postero-dorsal one. The maximum size is about 
<quantity id="5371B287FF9F5B49F98CBBC8B81C30B8" box="[250,331,1436,1461]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
in antero-posterior length (pers. comm., ter Poorten 2016). The sculpture consists of radial ribs, much finer anteriorly, wider and stronger on the remaining shell surface. Along the posterior margin, the radial ribs give origin to short, strong digitations (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FB3DBBB0BBDE30F0" box="[587,649,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C) that are almost interlocking when the shell is closed and occupying most of the posterior shell gape (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FB70B853BB11332C" box="[518,582,1543,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="94361F62FF9F5B49F9B1B878BCCE3284" blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
The fine anterior ribs are symmetrically triangular in cross section, then they become more and more asymmetrical (saw-tooth shaped) toward the posterior margin, with a wider, slightly convex anterior slope and a narrower, stepped posterior one (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FB7CB820BB1E3380" box="[522,585,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A, C). Near the posterior margin, the ribs are distinctly ridged and strongly asymmetrical, forming the digitate margin with their projections (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FAF6B8C3BA9633BC" box="[896,961,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C). The radial interspaces are narrow, flat and smooth, except for the posterior area, where they are narrow and deep. Well distinct crescent-shaped growth striae are present on the posterior ribs (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FB39B88BBBD833F4" box="[591,655,1759,1784]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C). No sculpture, except for growth striae, occurs on the ribs. Details on the hinge of 
<taxonomicName id="538964E1FF9F5B49F831B951B8ED3210" box="[327,442,1797,1820]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Bucardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ringens">
<emphasis id="A6FDC370FF9F5B49F831B951B8ED3210" box="[327,442,1797,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">B. ringens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were reported and commented by 
<bibRefCitation id="F0186293FF9F5B49FA49B950BD383210" author="Schneider" box="[831,1135,1796,1821]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Schneider, J. A. (2002) Phylogeny of cardiid bivalves (cockles and giant clams): revision of the Cardiinae and the importance of fossils in explaining disjunct biogeographical distributions. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 321 - 369. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00030. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Schneider (2002: fig. 12B)</bibRefCitation>
. In particular, he remarked the occurrence of striae on the lunular flap, a character shared with 
<taxonomicName id="538964E1FF9F5B49FADAB97CBD59324C" box="[940,1038,1832,1856]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Cardium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A6FDC370FF9F5B49FADAB97CBD59324C" box="[940,1038,1832,1856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cardium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some other 
<taxonomicName id="538964E1FF9F5B49FDA5B973BC17324C" box="[1235,1344,1831,1856]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Veneroida" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cardiinae">Cardiinae</taxonomicName>
genera. Schneider's illustration is not particularly clear, but the ridges on the lunular flap consist of a short, slightly oblique and somewhat irregular crenulation of the dorsal margin, more or less extending onto the lunular flap (
<figureCitation id="0CB203E7FF9F5B49FC65B93BBC053284" box="[1299,1362,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1394]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1395]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bucardium ringens (Bruguière, 1789). A – F. Casamance, Senegal, depth 10 – 20 m (ter Poorten coll., TP 634), photo J. J. ter Poorten, with permission (A – C, RV; D, LV). G, H. Hann Bay, Senegal, RV (La Perna coll.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/272520/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
G, H).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="94361F62FF9F5B49F9B1B9C0B98832F8" blockId="1.[151,1437,823,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
The species has a wide distribution in West Africa, from 
<collectingCountry id="EC9E5FF2FF9F5B49FA39B9C0BA9D32A1" box="[847,970,1940,1965]" name="Mauritania" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Mauritania</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="EC9E5FF2FF9F5B49FA86B9C0BD1532A1" box="[1008,1090,1940,1965]" name="Angola" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Angola</collectingCountry>
(about 20°N–20°S), including the 
<collectingCountry id="EC9E5FF2FF9F5B49F9B2B9ECB81E32DD" box="[196,329,1976,2001]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
Islands and 
<collectingCountry id="EC9E5FF2FF9F5B49F894B9ECBBA232DD" box="[482,757,1976,2001]" name="Sao Tome and Principe" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">
<collectingRegion id="564DD180FF9F5B49F894B9ECBB0132DC" box="[482,598,1976,2000]" country="Sao Tome and Principe" name="Sao Tome" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">São Tomé</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="564DD180FF9F5B49FBE3B9ECBBA232DD" box="[661,757,1976,2001]" country="Sao Tome and Principe" name="Principe" pageId="1" pageNumber="569">Príncipe</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, in 
<quantity id="5371B287FF9F5B49FA53B9ECBACE32DC" box="[805,921,1976,2001]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" unit="m" value="57.5" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="15.0">15–100 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F0186293FF9F5B49FADAB9ECBDD832DC" author="Fischer-Piette" box="[940,1167,1976,2001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Fischer-Piette, E. (1977) Revision des Cardiidae (Mollusques, Lamellibraches). Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, New Series, A, 101, 1 - 212." type="journal article" year="1977">Fischer-Piette 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F0186293FF9F5B49FDE9B9ECB98432F8" author="Voskuil" pageId="1" pageNumber="569" refString="Voskuil, R. P. &amp; Onverwagt, W. J. R. (1989) Inventarisation of the Recent European and West African Cardiidae (Mollusca, Bivalvia). Gloria Maris, 28, 49 - 96." type="journal article" year="1989">Voskuil &amp; Onverwagt 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
